          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/situationroom-1.jpg",
          "credit": "WHITE HOUSE - AI",
          "content": "### THE CABINET ROOM\n\n**The Atmosphere:**\nThe Cabinet Room has become a pressure cooker. Advisors have been meeting almost non-stop for 48 hours. Tempers are short. The table is littered with maps, intelligence briefs, and overflowing ashtrays. The group has fractured into two distinct camps: the 'Hawks' (favoring immediate military force) and the 'Doves' (favoring diplomacy).\n\n**The President's Fear:**\nPresident Kennedy is haunted by the history of World War I. He recently read *The Guns of August*, which detailed how European leaders in 1914 stumbled into a war no one wanted because their military plans were too rigid. He tells his advisors: *\"I am not going to follow a course which will allow anyone to write a comparable book about this time, 'The Missiles of October.'\"* He is looking for an option that allows for a pause—a moment for Khrushchev to think before the shooting starts."
        },
        "legal": {
          "label": "Hawk View",
          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/lemay.jpg",
          "credit": "USAF / GEN. LEMAY - AI",
          "content": "### PROFILE: GENERAL CURTIS LEMAY\n**Chief of Staff, US Air Force**\n\n**The Hawk Argument:**\nGeneral LeMay represents the hardline military stance. He views the crisis as a test of will. He argues that the Soviets only respect strength and that any diplomatic hesitation will be seen as weakness. He bluntly tells the President: *\"This is almost as bad as the appeasement at Munich.\"* This is a stinging insult, comparing Kennedy to the leaders who let Hitler take over Europe.\n\n**The Military Guarantee:**\nLeMay assures the room that the Air Force can execute a 'surgical strike' to destroy 90% of the missiles before they can be launched. When asked about the surviving 10%, he dismisses the risk, arguing that the US nuclear arsenal is vastly superior. He is willing to accept casualties now to prevent a greater Soviet threat later. To the Hawks, the Blockade is a half-measure that leaves the missiles in place."
        },
        "intel": {
          "label": "Dove View",
          "image": "https://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/cuba62/RFK-Mcnamara-1.jpg",
          "credit": "RFK & MCNAMARA - AI",
          "content": "### PROFILE: ROBERT MCNAMARA & RFK\n**The Dove Argument:**\nSecretary of Defense Robert McNamara and Robert Kennedy propose a different path: a **Naval Blockade**. However, they have a legal problem. Under international law, a 'blockade' is an act of war. It gives the blockaded nation the right to fight back.\n\n**The 'Quarantine' Solution:**\nTo navigate this legal minefield, they propose calling it a **'Strict Quarantine'** on offensive military equipment. It is a distinction without a difference physically, but diplomatically, it sounds less aggressive. It focuses only on weapons, allowing food and medicine to pass.\n\n**The Strategic Calculation:**\nMcNamara argues that the Blockade puts the ball in Khrushchev's court. If a war starts, it will be because a Soviet ship crossed a US line, not because a US bomb dropped on a Soviet camp. It buys time for negotiation and keeps the conflict at the conventional (non-nuclear) level for as long as possible."
